 A political earthquake has hit Virginia ahead of the crucial 2026 midterm elections after the Virginia Supreme Court blocked a Democrat-backed congressional redistricting map. The court ruled that Democratic lawmakers violated constitutional procedure while trying to place the amendment on the ballot, declaring the entire referendum “null and void.” The decision keeps Virginia’s current congressional map intact — a massive victory for Republicans as Democrats had hoped to flip up to four GOP-held House seats. The ruling could have major consequences for control of the U.S. House, where Democrats need just three seats nationwide to reclaim the majority. The court also rejected Democratic arguments over early voting rules, saying the constitutional violation undermined the integrity of the election process itself. Donald Trump celebrated the ruling as a huge win for Republicans, while top Democrats blasted the decision as undemocratic.
